# The Mentats · the human computers

In the universe of Dune, the thinking machines were outlawed after the Butlerian Jihad, whose commandment rang down the centuries: "Thou shalt not make a machine in the likeness of a human mind." Into the silence left by that prohibition stepped the Mentats — human beings trained to perform the logic and computation once surrendered to machines. They are the deliberate, disciplined answer to a question the species had forbidden itself to solve by easier means.

Through rigorous discipline a Mentat becomes a living computer, sifting vast oceans of data into prediction and strategy. Where a machine once ingested and calculated, now a trained human mind does the same work, drawing inference and projecting outcome from the raw material of fact. The Mentat is the embodiment of a paradox at the heart of the saga: a civilization that banned artificial intelligence reconstituted that intelligence in the only vessel left permitted to it — the human being.

This is why the Mentat's nature of emergence is electrical: it is the mind made machine. In a universe that outlawed thinking machines, the Mentat does not summon the unseen weave of prescience nor reach for the soul of the messiah; it computes. It is humanity's own faculty disciplined into the very instrument the Butlerian Jihad sought to abolish — the mind made into the very machine it forbade.
